description:
This is Nina Paley's &quot;OFFICIAL&quot; DVD version. This should be identical to the file content you would find on one of the DVDs you buy from her website (you should still buy a copy if you like the movie! hint hint!).

DVD features:
Director's Commentary featuring Nina Paley and Karl Fogel;
Subtitles including English, French, and *Italian;
25-minute interview* with creator/director Nina Paley;
Customized chapter selection screens with screenshot previews and animated backgrounds;
ONE trailer;
Full-resolution anamorphic 16x9 video with 16x9 menus;
Nina's original animated short film* &quot;Fetch!&quot;, in (moderately) high quality.
Please download, help seed, spread the word, and comment!

* = things not on my unofficial version. I'm super-jealous I couldn't get my hands on a good-quality copy of Fetch! to include. My version also has many more subtitle versions, but not Italian (you might notice my version has much better synchronization of subtitles, too). Still, the interview, Fetch, and the &quot;official&quot;ness make this version one to include in your collection.


Sita Sings the Blues
Directed, written, produced, designed and animated by Nina Paley
82 minutes
Animation
Color, stereo
2008

Synopsis:

Sita is a goddess separated from her beloved Lord and husband Rama. Nina is an animator whose husband moves to India, then dumps her by email. Three hilarious shadow puppets narrate both ancient tragedy and modern comedy in this beautifully animated interpretation of the Indian epic Ramayana. Set to the 1920's jazz vocals of Annette Hanshaw, Sita Sings the Blues earns its tagline as &quot;the Greatest Break-Up Story Ever Told.&quot;
